results.occurrenceRemarks: He was a very large seal, a male about 2.5m long and [the books say] probably weighing up to about 300 kilograms. The New Year crowd at Smitswinkel were mostly convinced that he had come ashore to pass away quietly, but one of the dozen or so veterinarians who frequent Smits every summer [no wonder there are always so many dogs] assured us that he was a healthy old fellow who had come shore to moult. Probably blown off-course by the Christmas Eve tidal surges that at Smits have left old kelp at least three metres higher up than the normal spring tides, the vet reckoned he would leave after a week or two. In the meantime he had a nice soft squishy bed of rotting and very odoriferous kelp to recline on, interacting rather passively with a variety of other organisms.
